definition: A common in vitro ADME assay that tests the stability of compounds when incubated with liver microsomes (subcellular fractions which contain membrane-bound drug-metabolizing enzymes).  Assay is used to measure in vitro intrinsic clearance or to identify metabolites formed. Typically liver microsomes from one or more mammalian species (mouse, rat, dog, monkey, human) are analyzed to understand differences in metabolism. Can be reported as % recovery after a set time (single timepoint), or as half-life (multiple timepoints).

A common in vitro ADME assay that tests the stability of compounds when incubated with plasma.  Assay is used to measure stability of new chemical entities in plasma, as compounds that rapidly degrade in plasma generally show poor in vivo efficacy. Typically lplasma from one or more mammalian species (mouse, rat, dog, monkey, human) are analyzed. Can be reported as % recovery after a set time (single timepoint), or as half-life (multiple timepoints).

A common in vitro ADME assay that uses the Caco-2 cell line (derived from human colon carcinoma) to assess transport in both directions (apical to basolateral (A-B) and basolateral to apical (B-A)) across the cell monolayer), to predict the in vivo absorption of drugs across the gut wall and to investigate drug efflux.
Physicochemical assays measure inherent properties of molecules, and include turbidimetric and thermodynamic solubility (in water or PBS), chemical stability, pKa, and lipophilicity (logP and logD)
A physicochemical assay that measures the maximum solubility of a molecule in a particular solvent (typically water or PBS).
An in vivo efficacy assay is a study perfromed in a whole, living organism (usually an animal such as a mouse or rat) to test the effects of a treatment on a specific disease modeled in this animal.

Gel electrophoresis is a method for separation and analysis of macromolecules (DNA, RNA and proteins) and their fragments, based on their size and charge. This general method encompasses different types of matrices (gels) with different properties. The most common types are polyacrylamide and agarose, both low-throughput methods.

Polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (PAGE), describes a technique to separate biological macromolecules, usually proteins or nucleic acids, according to their electrophoretic mobility. Mobility is a function of the length, conformation and charge of the molecule.  Gels can be native or denaturing (urea for nucleic acids, SDS for proteins).  A low-throughput method.

Agarose gel electrophoresis is a method to separate a mixed population of DNA or proteins in a matrix of agarose. The proteins may be separated by charge and/or size, and the DNA and RNA fragments by length, by applying an electric field to move the charged molecules through an agarose matrix.  A low-throughput method.
Coverslips are typically thin square pieces of glass
16 well electronic plate ('E Plate 16', (Roche Diagnostics)), used for electrophysiology

The word 'chip' is used to describe any flat surface (glass, plastic, other) that may be coated or treated to impart certain properties to help in either the immobilization and/or measurement of certain properties of varied macromolecules (protien, nucleic acid, small molecule). If an array of molecules is immobilized on a chip, the preferred term is 'array'.

Sensor chip CM5 is a chip used in Biacore (GE Healthcare) systems based on surface plasmon resonance (SPR) to measure molecular interactions with at least one molecule immobilized on a sensor surface. CM5 sensor chips have a matrix of carboxymethylated dextran covalently attached to a gold surface.

Assays performed in the pre-clinical development stage. These are assays on a lead candidate to develop it to an Investigative New Drug (IND). This stage typically includes both in vitro and in vivo assays, including thorough PK/PD profiling, toxicity, and in vivo dosing/ formulation optimization for efficacy.
Plasma is the liquid part of the blood and lymphatic fluid, which makes up about half of the volume of blood. Plasma is devoid of cells and, unlike serum, has not clotted.

Serum is the clear cell-free liquid that is separated from clotted blood. Serum differs from plasma in that the blood is first allowed to clot before centrifugation (separating from cells) while plasma preparations entail preventing blood clotting. Both are cell-free and contain antibodies.
Any  method that simply measures the overall abundance (concentration, relative amount, etc) of a particular molecule (lipids, second messenger, nucleic acid, protein, etc.)

Second messengers relay and amplify signals from receptors to the cell interior as part of a signaling event. Examples include cAMP, cGMP, calcium, nitric oxide, diacylglycerol, etc. Levels of these second messengers are measured to reflect strength of the signaling.
Measuring lipid abundance could include mass spec-based methods and lipid droplet formation, a fluorescent intensity+image analysis assay to measure lipid stored in droplets within a cell,
Cell density, typically measured by absorbance (often indicated as A600 or OD600), is often used for bacterial or fungal cultures as an indication of cell number, viability or proliferation.
Beta-galactosidase activity measurement method
Any  method that simply measures the overall abundance (concentration, relative amount, etc) of a nucleic acid (DNA or RNA), typically via hybridization methods

Any  method that simply measures the overall abundance (concentration, relative amount, etc) of a small molecule, such as LC-MS/MS or LC-UV. Typically used in both in vitro and in vivo ADME assays to monitor compound.
Any method that measures the size and shape of whole cells. Typically detected by microscopy or flow cytometry
Any method that measures the size and shape of structures or organelles within cells, such as nuclei, mitochindria, Golgi, ER or vesicles. Typically detected by microscopy or flow cytometry
Any study performed in a whole, living organism (usually an animal such as a mouse or rat).

Any study performed in a whole, living organism (usually an animal such as a mouse or rat), to test the effects of a treatment on a specific disease modeled in this animal. Study design and measured endpoints vary tremendously and depend on the particular aspects of the targeted disease. Ideally, the endpoints measured will correlate with how efficacy would be measured in humans.
Any study performed in a whole, living organism (usually an animal such as a mouse or rat) to investigate the pharmacokinetics (PK), pharmacodynamics (PD) or toxicity of a perturbagen or treatment.

Changes in protein thermal stability can be induced by ligand binding, and this thermodynamic stabilization can be measured by a variety of methods, often reported as a delta Tm (or change in the melting temperature of the protein).
Any method entailing primarily routine examination, requiring no special instrumentation.
Any method entailing basic measurements that require no special instrumentation. Examples are measuring a tumor size using calipers, or a subject's weight using a scale.
A synthetic ligand consisting of a small molecule tethered (covalently or non-covalently) to a peptide.

Any compound library consisting solely of small molecules that have been approved by the FDA. Often used for 'drug re-purposing' assays. The specific compounds included in any given FDA-approved compound library may differ based on availability or timing.
The concentration of compound required to kill 50% of a cell population (i.e., 50% inhibitory concentration in a cytotoxicity assay).

50% Tissue Culture Infective Dose (TCID50) is the measure of infectious virus titer. This endpoint dilution assay quantifies the amount of virus required to kill 50% of infected hosts or to produce a cytopathic effect in 50% of inoculated tissue culture cells.
A simple binary assessment, such as 'active/ inactive', 'true/ false', etc.

existing BAO class for proposed (super): Some form of 'subjective' result readout:  this uses a binary of 'true/false' for effect relative to DMSO control
definition: Any result reported as a simple binary assessment, such as 'active/ inactive', 'true/ false', etc.

proposed super class for proposed term (: Glo'-type assay by Promega for luminescent detection
definition: CytoTox-Glo Cytotoxicity Assay (Promega) uses a luminogenic peptide substrate of luciferase, the AAF-Glo Substrate, to measure dead-cell protease activity, which is released from cells that have lost membrane integrity.
The CAT ELISA is used to quantitatively measure CAT expression in eukaryotic cells that are transfected with a plasmid bearing a CAT-encoding reporter gene.

proposed term's name: ACTOne cAMP biosensor assay (BD Biosciences; CodexBIosolutions)
definition: This assay  directly measures the intracellular concentration of the second messenger cAMPin living cells, in real-time. It works with cell lines that contain a proprietary exogenous Cyclic Nucleotide-Gated (CNG) channel (BD Biosciences,  sold to CodexBiosolutions; both in Maryland). The channel is activated by elevated intracellular levels of cAMP, resulting in ion flux (detectable by calcium-responsive dyes) and cell membrane depolarization which can be detected with a fluorescent membrane potential (MP) dye.

The CellTiter-Blue Cell Viability Assay provides a homogeneous, fluorescent method for monitoring cell viability. The assay is based on the ability of living cells to convert a redox dye (resazurin) into a fluorescent end product (resorufin)

proposed term's name: Gal-Screen Beta-Galactosidase Reporter Gene Assay system
definition: The Gal-Screen assay system combines direct cell lysis with rapid, ultra-sensitive chemiluminescent detection of _-galactosidase reporter enzyme.
Real-time PCR (or RT-PCR) for quantitation of DNA (or RNA, respectively) using the fluorescent dye SYBR green that binds dsDNA and emits fluorescence only when bound.

Real-time PCR (or RT-PCR) for quantitation of DNA (or RNA, respectively) using a pair of unlabeled PCR primers and a 'TaqMan' fluorogenic probe  labeled on the 5' end and minor groove binder (MGB) and nonfluorescent quencher (NFQ) on the 3' end, to detect target as it accumulates during PCR.
Ultra-Glo (Promega) is a thermostable recombinant luciferase that can be coupled with different luciferin-based substrates to generate a luminescent signal proportional to the substrate abundance.

An assay system (Promega) based on the bioluminescent enzyme luciferase's catalysis of the substrate luciferin to generate light, adapted for multiple applications, such as cell viability, apoptosis, or kinase, cytochrome P450, or proteasome activity.

A colorimatric assay for cell viability/ proliferation based on the stable tetrazolium salt WST-1, which is cleaved to a soluble formazan by a complex cellular mechanism that occurs primarily at the cell surface. This bioreduction is largely dependent on the glycolytic production of NAD(P)H in viable cells.

proposed term's name: Reverse Transcription Kit (Applied Biosystems or ABI)

definition: A homogeneous bead-based proximity assay (alpha = 'amplified luminescent proximity homogeneous assay'). Binding of molecules captured on donor and acceptor beads leads to an energy transfer from one bead to the other, ultimately producing a luminescent/fluorescent signal.  Ligands on the bead allow for detection of many different types of molecules.
A homogeneous functional FRET-based assay used to assess both Ser/Thr and Tyr kinase activity
A solid phase sandwich ELISA to meaasure human cytochrome c in cell lysates

proposed term's name: TRANSCREENER ADP2 FP Kinase Assay (BellBrook Labs)
definition: A fluorescence polarization (FP) assay that uses an antibody against ADP and a tracer to measure the progress of any enzyme that produces ADP

proposed term's name: Polar Screen PPARg Competitor Assay, Green (Invitrogen)
definition: A fluorescence polarization (FP) assay.
QUANTI-Blue is a colorimetric enzyme assay to measure alkaline phosphatase activity.
The ToxiLighte BioAssay Kit is a bioluminescent cytolysis assay kit that measures release of the enzyme, adenylate kinase (AK), from damaged cells.

proposed term's name: TransAM Kit for NF-kB Family (Active Motif)
definition: TransAM Kits are DNA-binding ELISAs that facilitate the study of transcription factor activation in mammalian tissue and cell extracts.
A fluorescence polarization (FP) assay that uses an antibody against AMP or GMP and a tracer to measure the progress of any enzyme that produces AMP or GMP
A homogeneous, bioluminescent assay to measure caspase-6 activity.
CDP-Star is a chemiluminescent substrate of alkaline phosphatase, compatible with both membrane- and solution-based assays. Sold by multiple vendors.
An assay kit for measuring hepatitits C virus (HCV) NS3/4A protease activity using a 5-FAM/QXL520 fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET) peptide. Called 'Enzolyte' as well as 'Sensolyte'.

proposed term's name: EnzyChrom Aspartate Transaminase Assay Kit (BioAssay Systems)
definition: An absorbance-based assay system for measuring aspartate transaminase (known as serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase (GOT) or aspartate aminotransferase (ASAT/AAT)), based on the quantification of oxaloacetate produced by AST. In this assay, oxaloacetate and NADH are converted to malate and NAD by the enzyme malate dehydrogenase. The decrease in NADH absorbance at 340 nm is proportionate to AST activity.

proposed term's name: FluoZin-2 AM fluorescent assay of zinc concentration
definition: FluoZin-2 AM is a cell-permeant (acetoxymymethyl (AM)) fluorescent indicator designed to detect Zn2+ concentrations that are present in synaptic vesicles and released in response to electrical stimulation or excitotoxic agonists. (Sold by Molecular Probes, Themro-Fisher)

This homogeneous (HTRF) phospho-ERK assay is based on a TR-FRET sandwich immunoassay format comprising two specific monoclonal anti-pERK1/2 antibodies (recognizing the phosphorylated residue (Thr202/Tyr204), one labeled with Eu3+-cryptate (donor) and the other labeled with d2 (acceptor). The proximity of donor and acceptor leads to a fluorescent TR-FRET signal; the signal intensity is proportional to the substrate phosphorylation. Also called 'HTRF Cellul'ERK Kit'.

IMAP (Immobilized Metal Ion Affinity Particle) technology is a non-antibody-based assay for protein kinases in which a fluorescently labeled peptide substrate that is phosphorylated by a kinase is captured on trivalent metal-containing nanoparticles. IMAP can be adapted for either FP or TR-FRET detection.

This Insulin ELISA kit is an FDA registered in vitro diagnostic tool for the quantification of human insulin. It uses a dual-monoclonal antibody sandwich ELISA format, typically in a 96-well or other microplate format, with colorimetric (OD 450 nm) detection.

An assay to monitor protein ubiquitination, using ubiquitin labeled with the LanthaScreen terbium chelate, in combination with a FRET acceptor such as fluorescein-ubiquitin or a fluorescein-labeled antibody.
A terbium-labeled streptavidin used in combination with a fluorescent molecule to detect interaction via a TR-FRET assay.

proposed term's name: PathHunter U2OS Keap1-NRF2 Nuclear Translocation Assay (DiscoverX)
definition: An assay system employing enzyme fragment complementation (two fragments of the beta-galactosidase enzyme), applied in U2OS cells engineered to express two appropriately tagged proteins. Inhibition of Keap1-NRF2 interaction results in Nrf2 nuclear translocation, and susbequent complementation and formation of a functional enzyme, detected using a chemiluminescent substrate of beta-galactosidase.
A general kit for use in all types of qRT-PCR reactions
A bioluminescent assay sytem for detecting sea pansy (Renilla reniformis) luciferase, an alternative to the firefly (Photinus pyralis) systems.

An assay for deubiquitination activity, employing a reporter enzyme fused to ubiquitin (making the reporter catalytically inactive). Following cleavage of the Ub-reporter system by the isopeptidase, the free reporter can act upon its fluorescent substrate.
Automated patch clamp systems for ion channel research
Assay development system (plate-reader) with four modes: fluorescence, luminescence, absorbance, and Epi-absorbance (Molecular Devices)
An instument for single-channel recoding and whole-cell voltage-clamp recording (Axon Instruments/ Molecular Devices)
The BD LSRII FACS is an air-cooled multi-laser benchtop flow cytometer.

The Synergy 2 Multi-Mode Plate Reader's (BioTek) detection modes include fluorescence intensity, fluorescence polarization, time-resolved fluorescence, AlphaScreen, luminescence and UV-visible absorbance.

proposed term's name: BMG PHERAstar FSX plate reader (BMG Labtech, Cary NC)
definition: BMG PHERAstar is a multi-mode benchtop plate reader; FSX and other models (BMG Labtech)
An automated cell counting device: Countess; Countes II FL has fluorescence capabilites (Invitrogen/ ThermoFisher)
A flow cell_based benchtop cytometer (Becton Dickinson (BD))
A filter-based absorbance platereader for kinetic and endpoint assays (Molecualr Devices)
Several models of UV-visible absorbance microplate readers: SpectraMax 190; SpectraMax Plus 384; SpectraMax 340PC384 (Molecular Devices)
Several models of automated patch clamp systems for studying ion channels: QPatch8, QPAtch16, QpatchHT (Biolin Scientific)
One of several models of a plate-based real-time PCR device (Roche )
The Agilent Mx3005P QPCR System, a benchtop RT-PCR plate reader, has been replaced with the AriaMx system (Agilent Technologies)
The Synergy HT (or HTX) is a  Multi-Mode Plate Reader  (BioTek) is a single-channel absorbance, fluorescence and luminescence microplate reader.
One of several models of luminometer, either single-tube to multiple plate readers (Promega). Some models are multimode and can also read fluorescence or absorbance in addition to luminescence )
A mass spectrometer
Encompasses various models--ABI-9300, ABI-7500, and  QuantStudio.
A mass spectrometer

proposed term's name: VE-2 whole-cell patch clamp amplifier (Alembic Instruments)

definition: A microplate spectrophotometer

proposed term's name: SpectraMax Gemini XS microplate fluorometer (Molecular Devices)
Fluoroskan Ascent FL Microplate Fluorometer and Luminometer (ThermoFisher)
iMIC platform/ Polychrome V imaging system, (TILL Photonics/ FEI Munic GmbH)
TSQ Quantum Triple Quadrupole LC-MS (Thermo Scientific)
Typhoon Trio variable-mode imager (Amersham/ GE LifeSciences)
definition: A laser-based scanner that produces digital images of radioactive, fluorescent, or chemiluminescent samples

proposed term's name: xCELLigence RTCA DP cellular impedance instrument (Acea Biosciences)
definition: The xCELLigence RTCA DP instrument uses noninvasive electrical impedance monitoring to quantify cell proliferation, morphology change, and attachment quality in a label-free, real-time manner.
One of several models of surface plasmon resonance (SPR) instruments.
Imaging system based on CCD high-resolution detection, supports multiple detection methods including fluorescence, colorimetry, densitometry, chemiluminescence, and chemifluorescence.
An imaging system for blots, gels, etc, to replace use of film; can be used for autoradiography, fluorescence, and chemifluorescence imaging.
